    <section>
         <h2>Accessibility</h2>
        <p>Web accessibility is having the internet accessible to everyone including people with disabilities such as absence of hearing, speech, cognitive and motor skills. The internet has made a significant change to the world and has change how people are receiving and transmitting information to others. There various ways to access this information for people with disabilities. Instead of having to be dependent on other people to assist you with obtaining information -  physically and verbally,  there are programs such as text to speech, voice tying and intelligent assistant that help with people who have various types of disabilities to navigate the web. </p>
        <p>People that have vision disabilities can receive this information without having to depend on the published document having a braille version for them. They can simply press a button and a program can read to text to you, type a document with your voice along with many other possibilities. Furthermore, closed captioning has been a great for those who have hearing impairments.</p>
        <p>The same goes for people with motor skills disabilities. There are special computer equipment that accommodate to a personâ€™s disability such as specialized mice and keyboard. People that had trouble with turning a page of a book, newspaper or magazine can not easily any information they want via the internet.</p>
        <p>The web gives everyone freedom. It provides independence to people that are disabled in various shapes, ways and forms. Building the web with web accessibility in mind increased how many people in our society are able to do the undoable in the past and will help our society grow.</p>
    </section>
